WUTHERING HEIGHTS. 237

CHAPTER XII.

SUMMER was already past its prime, when
Edgar reluctantly yielded his assent to their
entreaties, and Catherine and I set out on our
ﬁrst ride to join her cousin.

“ It was a close, sultry day ; devoid of sun-
shine, but with a sky too dappled and hazy to
threaten rain; and our place of meeting had
been ﬁxed at the guide-stone, by the cross-
roads. On arriving there, however, a little
herd-boy, despatched as a messenger, told us
that—

